metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #496
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: Very Large Array #83
metadata.description: Very Large Array is a generative token by Leander Herzog. It creates one very large array to generate both visuals and audio. Made with javascript, webgl and the web audio api.

metadata.name: Down the Rabbit Hole #73
metadata.description:
Down the Rabbit Hole is a study in texture and intersecting shapes, inspired by Kandinsky, made with 100% code in p5.js.  I had a lot of fun with the textures.  You might get a 10Print maze as a texture!

Click open and then:
Press 2, 3, 4, or 5 to increase the pixel density.
Press g to add grain.
Press s to save a png.

Resize reverts to pixel density 1.  On a good machine, rendering at density 5 takes 8-10 seconds and adding grain at that density takes another 6 seconds.

I make gen art how-to videos on YouTube.  Come visit me at https://www.youtube.com/c/StevesMakerspace

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #372
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: .reflection #30
metadata.description:
Beauty has been an eternal theme since ancient times. Is there an absolutely immutable standard, or are there individual differences due to environment and time? Or is it determined democratically by the number of likes?

It was the philosopher Plato who proposed the "Idea Theory." He said that there is a world of truth (Idea world) that exists in another dimension from the sensory world we live in, where there is perfect "beauty" itself (Idea of beauty), and that things in the real world are recognized as beautiful because they contain fragments of this beauty. 

I have tried to express what the Idea is in my own way by referring to various things such as the surface of a lake, gemstones like Larimar, a sunset sky, a pale rainbow, pastel colors, geometry, and so on.

I hope you will think this work beautiful in your aesthetic sense!

Generative art by @ConatusLab

Built in Javascript with p5.js.

Press 's(S)' to save a png.

metadata.name: Eyeshadow Roses #537
metadata.description:
"Eyeshadow Roses" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

Painterly roses randomly overprinted with heavy streaks of ink. 

The roses grow by a sequence of three spirals, every new spiral smaller and superimposed on the former.  After the roses are fully formed, a random mask of heavy ink is algorithmically screened over the flowers in a pattern of horizontal or vertical lines, occasionally fully flooding the painting. The accumulation of choices evokes graffiti or printmaking. The sequence of choices are interpreted by the computer according to the algorithm. The beauty of these choices are determined by the viewer.

Each piece takes roughly 10 seconds to generate.

Artist: @sarah_ridgley
Press [s] to save the image
JavaScript / p5js | script size: 11kb

metadata.name: Ethereal Microcosm #27
metadata.description:
An exploration of algorithmic organisms in a contained environment.

This piece is about the simulation of microscopic patterns using a high number of even tinier agents all following the same rules. Different species evolve and interact together, resulting in stabilizing patterns out of their parametric configurations. A form of artificial life.

This work is based on the paper "Characteristics of pattern formation and evolution in approximations of physarum transport networks", written by Jeff Jones and popularized in the artistic field by Sage Jenson. Some features were added to increase the visual and behavioral complexity of the system. Agents are divided into different species, with their own set of rules and interacting with their own substrate. Substrates also interact with each other and agents will mutate in contact of some of them.

NFT License
